{South opens 1\H, his 5-card Major. North, with 14 points, naturally responds 2\D, forcing the partnership to game.

South next bids 2\S, showing the other Major suit. In standard bidding South would not be able to bid the \Ss since that would be a Reverse and South is far too weak to Reverse. But after a 2/1 Response the concept of a Reverse does not apply, and the priority of showing a 4-card Major certainly does apply.

North assumes South to be 4-5 in the Majors, so she cannot support either. She bids 2NT. If South actually has 6 \Hs (or 5 \Ss) he will rebid the suit. North's 2NT bid guarantees a stopper in the fourth suit.

South does not have either 6 \Hs or 5 \Ss so he just bids 3NT. Notice that South never once considered the possibility of passing what might be a misfit - the initial 2/1 response unconditionally forced the partnership to reach a game somewhere.}
